726
01:00:03.935 --> 01:00:05.867
- Montagu?
- Yes.


727
01:00:05.902 --> 01:00:09.895
This is D.N.I.
Scramble, will you?


728
01:00:12.342 --> 01:00:16.335
I've got a bit of news for you.
The major's arrived.


729
01:00:16.413 --> 01:00:19.447
I've just received a signal.

730
01:00:19.482 --> 01:00:22.083
The vice-counsel at Huelva
is very worried.


731
01:00:22.118 --> 01:00:25.555
He says the body carried
what looked like an official briefcase...


732
01:00:25.590 --> 01:00:28.392
and he's pulling every string
to retrieve it.


733
01:00:28.427 --> 01:00:31.159
Let's hope he doesn't
pull too hard, sir.


734
01:00:31.194 --> 01:00:35.187
Yes. But I think it might help
to keep the ball rolling if I make a signal...


735
01:00:35.498 --> 01:00:38.233
telling him to get hold
of it at all costs.

736
01:00:38.268 --> 01:00:41.337
If it was genuine, that would be
the natural thing to do, wouldn't it?


737
01:00:41.372 --> 01:00:43.304
Good.

738
01:00:43.339 --> 01:00:47.332
Meantime,
I'll put Major Martin in the casualty lists.


739
01:00:47.811 --> 01:00:51.112
- That's the first thing they'll check.
- Right.


740
01:00:59.422 --> 01:01:02.275
<i>Amen.</i>

741
01:01:05.163 --> 01:01:07.197
Amen.

742
01:01:11.601 --> 01:01:13.601
Amen.

743
01:01:34.591 --> 01:01:37.443
I called on the magistrate
before the funeral.


744
01:01:37.478 --> 01:01:40.589
All Major Martin's belongings
have been returned.


745
01:01:40.624 --> 01:01:43.700
- And the briefcase?
- Yes, and the briefcase.


746
01:01:43.735 --> 01:01:47.693
Good.

747
01:01:49.506 --> 01:01:52.040
<i>Well, that's a bit of a blow.</i>

748
01:01:52.075 --> 01:01:55.311
<i>Either Lawrence was too efficient</i>
<i>or the Nazis were too dumb.</i>


749
01:01:55.346 --> 01:01:57.412
The lazy, incompetent beggars.

750
01:01:57.447 --> 01:02:00.516
Doesn't anything ever penetrate
those Prussian skulls?


751
01:02:00.551 --> 01:02:03.586
The net result
of Operation Mincemeat so far...


752
01:02:03.621 --> 01:02:06.039
seems to be that
we've lost two bob.


753
01:02:06.074 --> 01:02:08.423
Everything else is horribly intact.

754
01:02:08.458 --> 01:02:11.744
Of course, sir,
there are ways of opening letters...


755
01:02:11.779 --> 01:02:15.031
apart from using a knife
with marmalade on it...


756
01:02:15.066 --> 01:02:19.024
and ways of closing them again.

757
01:02:19.802 --> 01:02:23.373
I'd like to hear
what the scientific boys have to say.


758
01:02:23.408 --> 01:02:27.366
Agreed.

759
01:02:34.284 --> 01:02:36.853
- Well?
- Course, this has been in water.


760
01:02:36.888 --> 01:02:40.846
Yes?

761
01:03:15.825 --> 01:03:17.859
- Seawater.
- Yes.


762
01:03:17.894 --> 01:03:21.197
It makes it very difficult when things
have been in water, particularly seawater.


763
01:03:21.232 --> 01:03:24.232
- Well, can you tell us anything?
- I'm afraid very little.


764
01:03:24.267 --> 01:03:28.260
You see, when the thing's been in water,
seawater, it obscures so much.


765
01:03:28.338 --> 01:03:30.974
- But do you think it's been opened?
- Opened?


766
01:03:31.009 --> 01:03:32.226
Oh, yes, it's been opened.

767
01:03:32.261 --> 01:03:33.443
Oh, yes, it's been opened.

768
01:03:33.478 --> 01:03:34.909
It has been opened?

769
01:03:34.944 --> 01:03:37.312
And closed again by somebody
who knows his business.


770
01:03:37.347 --> 01:03:41.117
It's been stretched out on a flat surface
and held lightly at the corners...


771
01:03:41.152 --> 01:03:43.151
probably to be photographed.

772
01:03:43.186 --> 01:03:46.022
- I only wish I could be more helpful.
- You've done splendidly.


773
01:03:46.057 --> 01:03:48.389
That's all we had to know.
Well?


774
01:03:48.424 --> 01:03:52.417
- Mincemeat swallowed whole.
- Mincemeat?


775
01:04:11.547 --> 01:04:13.014
Well?

776
01:04:13.049 --> 01:04:15.350
There's nothing new
from Madrid, Herr Admiral.


777
01:04:15.385 --> 01:04:18.021
The fÃ¼hrer has told his conference
that the documents...


778
01:04:18.056 --> 01:04:20.054
are undoubtedly genuine.

779
01:04:20.089 --> 01:04:23.008
- You mean he doesn't doubt them.
- He's quite sure.


780
01:04:23.043 --> 01:04:25.893
The fÃ¼hrer, of course,
has certain advantages...


781
01:04:25.928 --> 01:04:29.499
over mere intelligence officers
like you and me, Frederik.


782
01:04:29.534 --> 01:04:31.899
He has his intuition...

783
01:04:31.934 --> 01:04:35.203
whereas we have to
rely on our brains.


784
01:04:35.238 --> 01:04:39.231
- And he's sure God is on his side.
- But you are not?


785
01:04:39.475 --> 01:04:42.745
I do not believe
that God is on my side to the extent...


786
01:04:42.780 --> 01:04:46.047
of handing me the enemy's plans.

787
01:04:46.082 --> 01:04:50.075
There's no way in which we can check
the genuineness of these papers.


788
01:04:54.357 --> 01:04:58.350
<i>Those certainly appear to be</i>
<i>Nye's and Mountbatten's signatures.</i>


789
01:05:02.298 --> 01:05:06.291
The question is whether
what is in the letters is true.


790
01:05:07.904 --> 01:05:11.897
And only the people
who wrote them could tell us.


791
01:05:11.974 --> 01:05:14.175
But we can do something...

792
01:05:14.210 --> 01:05:16.879
to check the genuineness of the bearer.

793
01:05:16.914 --> 01:05:18.980
In what sense, Herr Admiral?

794
01:05:19.015 --> 01:05:23.008
We know a great deal about
the lamented Major Martin, Frederik.


795
01:05:23.453 --> 01:05:27.446
We know the address
of his club, of his bank.


796
01:05:27.924 --> 01:05:30.658
We even know about his debts.

797
01:05:30.693 --> 01:05:34.686
I think someone had better ask
a few discreet questions in London...


798
01:05:35.231 --> 01:05:38.401
just to make sure
there was such a man.


799
01:05:53.082 --> 01:05:55.151
- From Dublin, Mr. O'Reilly?
- That's right.


800
01:05:55.186 --> 01:05:57.220
- How long are you staying?
- Uh, three days.


801
01:05:57.255 --> 01:05:59.389
- London?
- Yeah.


802
01:05:59.424 --> 01:06:01.489
- Business?
- Yes.


803
01:06:01.524 --> 01:06:05.517
- All right. Thank you.
- Thank you.


804
01:06:14.003 --> 01:06:16.204
- Is this all your luggage?
- Uh, yes.


805
01:06:16.239 --> 01:06:18.808
- Will you read this notice, please?
- I have.


806
01:06:18.843 --> 01:06:21.377
- Have you any articles subject to duty?
- No.


807
01:06:21.412 --> 01:06:25.370
All right.
I'll open this one up.


808
01:06:27.583 --> 01:06:31.576
All right. Thank you.
Shut it up again.


809
01:06:32.722 --> 01:06:35.558
Is this all your luggage, madam?

810
01:06:35.593 --> 01:06:38.359
Will you read this notice, please?

811
01:06:38.394 --> 01:06:42.387
Do you have any articles
subject to duty?


812
01:07:02.051 --> 01:07:05.955
Will you drive me to Number 57
Landsmere Gardens, please?


813
01:07:05.990 --> 01:07:09.137
57 Landsmere Gardens?

814
01:07:09.172 --> 01:07:12.284
All right. Step in.

815
01:07:22.405 --> 01:07:25.341
I trust you had a pleasant journey.

816
01:07:25.376 --> 01:07:28.277
I am here with thee and thy goats.

817
01:07:28.312 --> 01:07:30.311
- Where from?
- Dublin.


818
01:07:30.346 --> 01:07:33.549
If you look over your head,
you'll see a plate with a telephone number.


819
01:07:33.584 --> 01:07:37.542
Memorize it,
but don't write it down.


820
01:07:37.787 --> 01:07:40.788
If it's absolutely necessary,
but not otherwise...


821
01:07:40.823 --> 01:07:43.392
ring that number for a cab to pick you up
outside the south entrance...


822
01:07:43.427 --> 01:07:45.728
to the tube station at Hyde Park Corner.

823
01:07:45.763 --> 01:07:47.895
Go straight there and wait for me.

824
01:07:47.930 --> 01:07:50.950
But don't ring unless it's important.
You're not under my orders.


825
01:07:50.985 --> 01:07:53.935
I'm not responsible for you,
and I have troubles enough of my own.


826
01:07:53.970 --> 01:07:57.206
My instructions simply are to meet you
and deliver you and your luggage. That's all.


827
01:07:57.241 --> 01:08:00.575
I doubt if I shall bother you much.

828
01:08:00.610 --> 01:08:04.603
It's nothing to do with me,
but why were you chosen for this job?


829
01:08:05.681 --> 01:08:09.674
Because I'm so fond of the English.

830
01:08:10.820 --> 01:08:14.218
Yes, they are a loveable people.

831
01:08:14.253 --> 01:08:17.616
<i>Hey!</i>

832
01:08:27.703 --> 01:08:31.639
Your other bag, sir.

833
01:08:31.674 --> 01:08:35.678
- Thank you.
- Three and sixpence on the clock, sir.


834
01:08:35.713 --> 01:08:39.671
Thank you, sir.
Jolly good luck, sir.


835
01:08:52.595 --> 01:08:54.330
- Uh, yes?
- My name's O'Reilly.


836
01:08:54.365 --> 01:08:56.030
I believe you have a room for me.

837
01:08:56.065 --> 01:08:58.599
- Oh, you're the gentleman from Dublin?
- That's right.


838
01:08:58.634 --> 01:09:02.627
- Oh, yes. Of course. Will you come in, please?
- Thank you.


839
01:09:05.174 --> 01:09:08.744
Well, I'll take you straight up, shall I?
Give me one of your cases.


840
01:09:08.779 --> 01:09:10.711
Oh, I can manage.

841
01:09:10.746 --> 01:09:13.983
- Never let it be said I let a lady carry for me.
- Oh, you're all the same.


842
01:09:14.018 --> 01:09:16.719
I always say there's
nobody like the Irish for manners.


843
01:09:16.754 --> 01:09:19.086
My granddad was Irish.
He came from the north.


844
01:09:19.121 --> 01:09:21.840
But as he said,
"What does it matter, north or south?


845
01:09:21.875 --> 01:09:24.525
We're all Irish,
and all the Irish are kings' sons. "


846
01:09:24.560 --> 01:09:28.175
Now, look,
I've put you on the first floor here.


847
01:09:28.210 --> 01:09:31.790
That's the bathroom and the necessary,
and this is your room.


848
01:09:33.736 --> 01:09:37.729
I do hope you'll be comfortable.

849
01:09:38.474 --> 01:09:41.844
I expect you'd like a cup of tea, wouldn't you?
I can make you one quite easily.


850
01:09:41.879 --> 01:09:45.546
Oh, no, thank you.
I'll just get on and unpack my things.


851
01:09:45.581 --> 01:09:48.884
<i>Oh, the blackout. Oh, you will be careful</i>
<i>about the blackout, won't you?</i>


852
01:09:48.919 --> 01:09:52.855
Do you know I had the police
round three times about it last week?


853
01:09:52.890 --> 01:09:56.025
Oh, don't worry.
I'll be very careful.


854
01:09:56.060 --> 01:09:59.161
Well, I'll leave you to yourself now.

855
01:09:59.196 --> 01:10:01.128
Oh, I almost forgot.

856
01:10:01.163 --> 01:10:05.156
In case you should want to be out late in the
evening, I'll put the key on the hall table.


857
01:10:05.568 --> 01:10:09.338
And if there's anything else you want, just call
"coo-ee" over the banisters and I'll pop up.


858
01:10:09.373 --> 01:10:13.331
Thank you.

859
01:11:37.960 --> 01:11:41.030
Polar... bear.

860
01:11:41.065 --> 01:11:44.495
Polar... bear.

861
01:11:44.530 --> 01:11:47.926
Stand by tonight.

862
01:12:03.919 --> 01:12:07.912
Well, the tie.
The darkish blue goes with this suit.


863
01:12:08.791 --> 01:12:12.561
Yes, with pinstripes
right through it, if we can.


864
01:12:12.596 --> 01:12:16.554
Thank you very much, sir.
Good morning.


865
01:12:18.000 --> 01:12:21.993
- Good morning, sir.
- Uh, um, I'd like some khaki shirts, please.


866
01:12:22.404 --> 01:12:25.474
- Made to measure or ready-made, sir?
- Ready-made.


867
01:12:25.509 --> 01:12:29.467
- Collar size?
- Sixteen.


868
01:12:30.846 --> 01:12:33.280
I think you'll like these, sir.

869
01:12:33.315 --> 01:12:35.850
They're very fine poplin.
Practically prewar quality.


870
01:12:35.885 --> 01:12:38.621
- Oh, yes, yes. They're very nice indeed.
- It's a beautiful shirt, sir.


871
01:12:38.656 --> 01:12:41.490
- But they're not really the ones I had in mind.
- No, sir?


872
01:12:41.525 --> 01:12:45.127
No, you sold some to a friend of mine
a few weeks ago.


873
01:12:45.162 --> 01:12:48.496
Um, Major William Martin
of the Royal Marines.


874
01:12:48.531 --> 01:12:52.524
- They were cotton with separate collars.
- I know the one you mean.


875
01:12:54.970 --> 01:12:57.540
Just take a look
at those, will you, sir?

876
01:12:57.575 --> 01:13:00.508
Separate collars. Cotton.

877
01:13:00.543 --> 01:13:02.545
- Oh, good morning, sir.
- Good morning.


878
01:13:02.580 --> 01:13:06.538
- Won't keep you a moment.
- Right.


879
01:13:07.917 --> 01:13:10.452
- Yes, these look like the ones.
- Good, sir.


880
01:13:10.487 --> 01:13:12.720
But I'm not quite sure.

881
01:13:12.755 --> 01:13:16.748
Uh, would it be troubling you too much
to look up Major Martin's account...


882
01:13:16.992 --> 01:13:19.360
Look, sir, if your friend
got his shirts from us...


883
01:13:19.395 --> 01:13:22.298
and if they were cotton with separate collars,
those are certainly the ones.


884
01:13:22.333 --> 01:13:25.833
- We haven't any others in stock.
- Oh.


885
01:13:25.868 --> 01:13:29.549
Well, I'll not doubt the word
of an honest man.


886
01:13:29.584 --> 01:13:33.231
- I'll take two.
- Thank you very much, sir.


887
01:13:33.909 --> 01:13:36.979
- <i>So I said to this chap, if you can't let us have...</i>
- Excuse me.


888
01:13:37.014 --> 01:13:40.333
- Is this the Naval and Military Club?
- Yes, that's right.


889
01:13:40.368 --> 01:13:43.652
- Thank you.
- Well, you might as well scrap the whole idea.


890
01:13:57.299 --> 01:14:01.292
I wonder if you could help me.

891
01:14:04.340 --> 01:14:06.909
I wonder if you could help me.

892
01:14:06.944 --> 01:14:08.876
I'll do my best, sir.

893
01:14:08.911 --> 01:14:11.914
I'm looking for a friend of mine,
Major Martin.


894
01:14:11.949 --> 01:14:15.751
Major William Martin
of the Royal Marines.


895
01:14:15.786 --> 01:14:17.952
I believe he's a member here.

896
01:14:17.987 --> 01:14:20.889
Do you happen to have seen him lately
or know his whereabouts?


897
01:14:20.924 --> 01:14:24.291
Major Martin.
There's a Major Martin who's a gunner, sir.


898
01:14:24.326 --> 01:14:28.297
No, that'd hardly be him.
He's in the Royal Marines.


899
01:14:28.332 --> 01:14:30.497
- Eh?
- The Royal Marines!


900
01:14:30.532 --> 01:14:33.102
I don't think I know
the gentleman personally, sir.


901
01:14:33.137 --> 01:14:35.521
Is he a regular officer or temporary?

902
01:14:35.556 --> 01:14:37.871
Oh, now, there I couldn't be sure.

903
01:14:37.906 --> 01:14:40.709
If he's a temporary,
I probably shouldn't know him, sir.


904
01:14:40.744 --> 01:14:44.046
There's a lot of members now
that I don't know.


905
01:14:44.081 --> 01:14:46.949
"Martin, Brigadier A.T."

906
01:14:46.984 --> 01:14:50.103
"Martin, Captain L."

907
01:14:50.138 --> 01:14:53.187
"Martin, Major W., R.A."

908
01:14:53.222 --> 01:14:56.992
No, sir. No Major Martin
what's a marine here, sir.


909
01:14:57.027 --> 01:15:00.728
- Now, surely that's odd if he's a member.
- Eh?


910
01:15:00.763 --> 01:15:04.698
- Surely that's odd if he's a member!
- Not necessarily, sir.


911
01:15:04.733 --> 01:15:08.726
What with the bomb damage and no staff,
we're a bit behind with things these days.


912
01:15:09.438 --> 01:15:12.539
If he's a new member,
he may not be on the file yet.


913
01:15:12.574 --> 01:15:16.312
You could leave a message. Then if he
comes in, I'll personally see he gets it.


914
01:15:16.347 --> 01:15:18.345
No, thanks.
It can wait.


915
01:15:18.380 --> 01:15:21.283
- I'm grateful to you, all the same.
- Eh?


916
01:15:21.318 --> 01:15:24.353
I'm grateful to ya, all the same!

917
01:15:24.388 --> 01:15:28.346
Oh. Thank you, sir.

918
01:15:40.002 --> 01:15:43.995
<i>This is the manager's secretary speaking.</i>
<i>Who is it, please? Thank you.</i>


919
01:15:46.742 --> 01:15:50.735
Will you hold on a moment, please?

920
01:15:57.619 --> 01:16:00.254
There's the contract you asked for.

921
01:16:00.289 --> 01:16:03.887
And there's a Mr. Phillips who'd
like to speak to you on the phone.


922
01:16:03.922 --> 01:16:07.485
- What does he want?
- He's making inquiries about a Major Martin.


923
01:16:08.497 --> 01:16:12.490
- About who?
- A Major Martin.


924
01:16:15.237 --> 01:16:17.271
Put him through.

925
01:16:17.306 --> 01:16:20.042
Stay on the line and get
a shorthand note of what we say.


926
01:16:20.077 --> 01:16:24.035
Yes, Mr. Emberton.

927
01:16:24.346 --> 01:16:26.313
Switchboard.

928
01:16:26.348 --> 01:16:28.882
- There's a call on my outside line.
- Yes, sir?


929
01:16:28.917 --> 01:16:32.910
- Get through to the exchange and have it traced.
- Yes, sir.


930
01:16:37.426 --> 01:16:39.495
- Hello.
- Is that the manager?


931
01:16:39.530 --> 01:16:42.796
Speaking.

932
01:16:42.831 --> 01:16:45.199
L
- I wonder if you could help me.

933
01:16:45.234 --> 01:16:49.227
My name is Phillips, and I'm making
some inquiries about Major William Martin.


934
01:16:49.872 --> 01:16:53.865
- Yes?
- I believe he was a customer of yours.


935
01:16:54.743 --> 01:16:57.913
Only the poor fellow's dead,
and as an old friend...


936
01:16:57.948 --> 01:17:00.482
I'm trying to help clear up his affairs.

937
01:17:00.517 --> 01:17:03.250
I see.

938
01:17:03.285 --> 01:17:07.278
I'm sure you'll understand it's an absolute rule
of the bank not to discuss a client's affairs...


939
01:17:07.423 --> 01:17:10.259
with anyone
but his accredited representatives.


940
01:17:10.294 --> 01:17:12.793
Certainly not on the telephone.

941
01:17:12.828 --> 01:17:15.362
But I am onto the right branch,
I take it.


942
01:17:15.397 --> 01:17:19.334
I should have thought the best thing
would be if you could drop in and see me.


943
01:17:19.369 --> 01:17:23.327
I'm pretty full up this morning,
but this afternoon's all right...


944
01:17:24.239 --> 01:17:28.232
if you'd like to come in at, say,
quarter past 2:00 and ask for me.


945
01:17:28.877 --> 01:17:32.781
Yes. Yes, I suppose
that would be a good idea.


946
01:17:32.816 --> 01:17:35.517
- A quarter past 2:00.
- Yes.


947
01:17:35.552 --> 01:17:39.510
All right.

948
01:17:55.604 --> 01:17:58.340
You were very smart
to get this, Mr. Emberton.


949
01:17:58.375 --> 01:18:01.076
My secretary often takes notes
of important calls.


950
01:18:01.111 --> 01:18:03.110
You say he had a slight accent?

951
01:18:03.145 --> 01:18:06.215
Yes, but, uh, not a foreign accent,
if you follow me.


952
01:18:06.250 --> 01:18:08.582
It's difficult to tell on the telephone.

953
01:18:08.617 --> 01:18:11.269
I should have said he was English,
but possibly from the west country.


954
01:18:11.304 --> 01:18:13.922
- Did you trace the call?
- It came from a public telephone booth.


955
01:18:13.957 --> 01:18:17.143
Obviously, yet when you
suggested an appointment, he agreed.


956
01:18:17.178 --> 01:18:20.205
He agreed, but he didn't sound
particularly enthusiastic.


957
01:18:20.240 --> 01:18:23.197
Is there any chance
that this might be a coincidence?


958
01:18:23.232 --> 01:18:27.002
William Martin is quite a common name.
He may have just mistaken the bank.


959
01:18:27.037 --> 01:18:29.269
- It's possible, but...
- But not probable.


960
01:18:29.304 --> 01:18:32.975
Well, thank you very much, Mr. Emberton.
You've handled the whole thing beautifully.


961
01:18:33.010 --> 01:18:35.509
Frankly, I don't think
the man will turn up.


962
01:18:35.544 --> 01:18:39.281
However, we can't afford to take any chances.
We'll both be back at 2:00.


963
01:18:39.316 --> 01:18:43.285
- I'll be waiting for you.
- Thank you.


964
01:18:43.320 --> 01:18:46.119
- He's a good chap.
- Very good.


965
01:18:46.154 --> 01:18:50.147
Look, George, if there's somebody around
who can ring up Willie Martin's bank...


966
01:18:50.225 --> 01:18:54.218
it means that Jerryâ€™s putting the whole thing
under a microscope.


967
01:18:54.530 --> 01:18:58.523
Now, where, if anywhere,
is there a weak link?


968
01:19:00.802 --> 01:19:04.795
I'm going to Scotland Yard to talk
to General Colbourne of the special branch.


969
01:19:06.608 --> 01:19:09.611
Of course, a voice from a telephone booth
isn't much of a starting point.


970
01:19:09.646 --> 01:19:11.578
I realize that, sir.

971
01:19:11.613 --> 01:19:15.606
I wondered whether you'd had any ripple on
the waters recently that might give us a line.


972
01:19:16.285 --> 01:19:18.285
I don't think so.

973
01:19:18.320 --> 01:19:21.089
There's a gentleman just arrived from Sweden
we're rather interested in...


974
01:19:21.124 --> 01:19:23.590
but he's nothing to do
with your Major Martin.


975
01:19:23.625 --> 01:19:27.563
It's certain he won't come to the bank, but we'd
better have a couple of your men just in case.


976
01:19:27.598 --> 01:19:30.466
Yes, of course.
We must certainly be in on it.


977
01:19:30.501 --> 01:19:33.119
We always like to make
a new friend if we can.


978
01:19:33.154 --> 01:19:35.702
Besides, you may be wrong.
He may turn up.


979
01:19:35.737 --> 01:19:38.307
My guess is that he's only over here
for this one job.


980
01:19:38.342 --> 01:19:41.605
He knows we haven't
got our tabs on him.


981
01:19:41.640 --> 01:19:44.869
He's the sort of man
who might take chances.


982
01:20:30.659 --> 01:20:33.495
- <i>A washout.</i>
- <i>Yes, sir.</i>


983
01:20:33.530 --> 01:20:36.465
- We'll get back and stand by.
- Right.


984
01:20:36.500 --> 01:20:39.366
Pity. Do you think
he suspected Emberton?


985
01:20:39.401 --> 01:20:43.394
I don't know, but it's obvious
he can't afford to show himself.


986
01:22:12.861 --> 01:22:15.597
- Hello?
- Is that the American Library?


987
01:22:15.632 --> 01:22:18.333
- Yes.
- Can I speak to Miss Sherwood, please?


988
01:22:18.368 --> 01:22:20.300
Just a moment.

989
01:22:20.335 --> 01:22:23.905
Lucy, it's for you, and you really must get him
to ring up out of working hours.


990
01:22:23.940 --> 01:22:26.575
I'm sorry. I'll tell him.
Hello? Hello, Joe?


991
01:22:26.610 --> 01:22:30.568
Lucy, this is Larry.

992
01:22:31.713 --> 01:22:35.706
- Hello, Larry.
- You know why I'm phoning, don't you, Lu?


993
01:22:36.017 --> 01:22:40.010
Sure. Sure.

994
01:22:43.825 --> 01:22:47.818
Oh, no, he's gone.
I guess I knew it would come.


995
01:22:48.563 --> 01:22:52.556
Thank you, Larry.
You all right?


996
01:22:54.002 --> 01:22:57.005
Yes, he was a good flyer.

997
01:22:57.040 --> 01:22:59.973
Thank you for ringing, Larry.

998
01:23:00.008 --> 01:23:04.001
<i>Would you check this book out,</i>
<i>please, miss?</i>


999
01:23:53.829 --> 01:23:57.076
<i>Lucy!</i>

1000
01:23:57.111 --> 01:24:00.324
<i>Lucy?</i>

1001
01:24:27.829 --> 01:24:31.031
Good evening.

1002
01:24:31.066 --> 01:24:35.059
I'm sorry to disturb you,
but the door was open.


1003
01:24:35.136 --> 01:24:37.537
Yes.
What do you want?


1004
01:24:37.572 --> 01:24:41.565
I'm making some inquiries
about a friend of mine, William Martin.


1005
01:24:43.044 --> 01:24:47.037
- William Martin?
- Yes.


1006
01:24:47.382 --> 01:24:51.375
- Yes, will you come in?
- Thank you.


1007
01:24:57.492 --> 01:24:59.693
Won't you sit down?

1008
01:24:59.728 --> 01:25:03.064
Willie's death was a great shock to me.

1009
01:25:03.099 --> 01:25:07.057
Yes, it was a great pity.

1010
01:25:08.336 --> 01:25:11.806
Forgive me, but I take it
you're not his fiancÃ©e.


1011
01:25:11.841 --> 01:25:14.307
No. I hardly knew him.

1012
01:25:14.342 --> 01:25:17.412
Only I understood
he'd just recently become engaged...


1013
01:25:17.447 --> 01:25:20.181
and that his fiancÃ©e
lived at this address.


1014
01:25:20.216 --> 01:25:22.148
That's why I came.

1015
01:25:22.183 --> 01:25:26.176
Yes, well, that's the girl who
lives here with me... Lucy Sherwood.


1016
01:25:26.721 --> 01:25:30.714
Oh, will you have a cigarette?

1017
01:25:34.229 --> 01:25:38.222
Thank you.

1018
01:25:38.433 --> 01:25:42.304
Lucy Sherwood.
That's right. I remember.


1019
01:25:42.339 --> 01:25:46.297
I'll get you a light.

1020
01:25:46.975 --> 01:25:49.009
I should have liked to see her.

1021
01:25:49.044 --> 01:25:52.263
- I'm afraid she's out tonight.
- When will she be back?


1022
01:25:52.298 --> 01:25:55.542
Not until late, but if you could
come again tomorrow...


1023
01:25:55.577 --> 01:25:58.787
I'd say that you'd called
and that you'd be coming back.


1024
01:25:58.822 --> 01:26:02.780
Yes.

1025
01:26:04.926 --> 01:26:08.919
I knew Willie right from the time
when he was a boy in Cardiff.


1026
01:26:09.931 --> 01:26:12.500
Did he come from Cardiff?
I didn't know.


1027
01:26:12.535 --> 01:26:14.736
Is his fiancÃ©e very upset?

1028
01:26:14.771 --> 01:26:18.004
Well, naturally.

1029
01:26:18.039 --> 01:26:20.573
Well, I don't want
to take up your time...

1030
01:26:20.608 --> 01:26:23.476
but I do want to...
to do everything I can to help.


1031
01:26:23.511 --> 01:26:26.081
So if you would like to give his fiancÃ©e
my name and address...


1032
01:26:26.116 --> 01:26:29.783
- Your address?
- Yes.


1033
01:26:29.818 --> 01:26:33.811
Perhaps you'd care to take it down.

1034
01:26:45.133 --> 01:26:47.769
My name is Patrick O'Reilly.

1035
01:26:47.804 --> 01:26:51.671
R
- E
-I-double L
-Y.

1036
01:26:51.706 --> 01:26:55.699
And my address is

1037
01:26:56.478 --> 01:27:00.471
North West 1.

1038
01:27:01.649 --> 01:27:05.153
I am to be found there any time.

1039
01:27:05.188 --> 01:27:09.146
Right.

1040
01:27:16.031 --> 01:27:18.565
Oh. Sorry.

1041
01:27:18.600 --> 01:27:21.636
Don't mind me.
I'm just passing through.


1042
01:27:21.671 --> 01:27:24.105
You're Miss Lucy Sherwood?

1043
01:27:24.140 --> 01:27:26.306
That's right.

1044
01:27:26.341 --> 01:27:30.334
Well, go on. Where's your manners, Pam?
Introduce your handsome friend.


1045
01:27:30.412 --> 01:27:34.293
- Lucy, this is Mr. Patrick O'Reilly.
- Hello there.


1046
01:27:34.328 --> 01:27:38.175
Mr. O'Reilly is making inquiries
about Willie Martin.


1047
01:27:38.219 --> 01:27:40.353
Willie Martin?

1048
01:27:40.388 --> 01:27:44.381
Willie Martin.
Dearest Willie?


1049
01:27:44.459 --> 01:27:47.695
It's no good making inquiries
about him, mister.


1050
01:27:47.730 --> 01:27:51.688
Willie Martin doesn't exist.

1051
01:27:55.970 --> 01:27:59.963
At least he's dead,
which is the same thing.


1052
01:28:00.041 --> 01:28:03.272
That's right, isn't it?
That's true.


1053
01:28:03.307 --> 01:28:06.503
<i>He's dead, so he doesn't exist.</i>

1054
01:28:06.881 --> 01:28:10.874
It's the same with all these boys.
Here today, gone tomorrow.


1055
01:28:12.053 --> 01:28:14.087
What's real about that?

1056
01:28:14.122 --> 01:28:17.292
I was very sorry
to hear of his death.

1057
01:28:17.327 --> 01:28:20.026
Why should you be sorry?

1058
01:28:20.061 --> 01:28:23.164
You weren't in love
with him, were you?


1059
01:28:23.199 --> 01:28:26.267
He didn't give you a ring.
I never wore it.


1060
01:28:26.302 --> 01:28:29.102
<i>Now I never will.</i>

1061
01:28:29.137 --> 01:28:32.839
<i>Ever! Ever!</i>

1062
01:28:32.874 --> 01:28:36.867
- Lucy.
- I knew him in the old days in Cardiff.


1063
01:28:37.278 --> 01:28:41.271
Did you, now?
And I'll bet you knew his old man too.


1064
01:28:41.349 --> 01:28:45.342
His ma and his sister
and the whole shooting match.


1065
01:28:45.487 --> 01:28:49.422
Well, I didn't.
They were just photographs.


1066
01:28:49.457 --> 01:28:53.450
The usual photographs
with folks looking the way folks do.


1067
01:28:54.262 --> 01:28:56.463
But I never knew 'em.

1068
01:28:56.498 --> 01:28:59.945
In the time, I barely knew <i>him.</i>

1069
01:28:59.980 --> 01:29:03.393
Three months.
What sort of time's that?


1070
01:29:09.777 --> 01:29:13.770
And yet I knew him well enough.

1071
01:29:13.982 --> 01:29:16.551
And then they took him away from me...

1072
01:29:16.586 --> 01:29:19.955
and killed him in the sea.

1073
01:29:19.990 --> 01:29:23.289
"Down, down into the sea...

1074
01:29:23.324 --> 01:29:25.827
to be lost evermore in the main. "

1075
01:29:25.862 --> 01:29:28.161
<i>Tennyson.</i>

1076
01:29:28.196 --> 01:29:30.265
<i>Do you know Tennyson?</i>

1077
01:29:30.300 --> 01:29:32.632
Why should you?

1078
01:29:32.667 --> 01:29:35.837
Why should I know Tennyson?

1079
01:29:35.872 --> 01:29:38.838
He almost made it.

1080
01:29:38.873 --> 01:29:42.610
Darling, I dreamed you.
I was always afraid I had.


1081
01:29:42.645 --> 01:29:45.345
Always afraid.

1082
01:29:45.380 --> 01:29:48.366
Lucy, darling,
I really think you ought to go to bed.


1083
01:29:48.401 --> 01:29:51.317
Bed? What for?
There's plenty of time to go to bed.


1084
01:29:51.352 --> 01:29:54.689
Years and years with nothing else to do
and nowhere else to go.


1085
01:29:54.724 --> 01:29:57.323
And everything cold and ended.

1086
01:29:57.358 --> 01:30:00.228
Oh, why can't you all go away
and let me alone?


1087
01:30:09.771 --> 01:30:12.540
- Is she all right?
- Yes, I think so.


1088
01:30:12.575 --> 01:30:15.276
But I really must get her to bed.

1089
01:30:15.311 --> 01:30:17.462
I'm sorry I've intruded.

1090
01:30:17.497 --> 01:30:19.614
You have my address.

1091
01:30:19.649 --> 01:30:23.607
Yes.

1092
01:30:27.323 --> 01:30:29.389
Lucy. Lucy.

1093
01:31:02.357 --> 01:31:05.226
Polar... bear.

1094
01:31:05.261 --> 01:31:08.513
Polar... bear.

1095
01:31:08.548 --> 01:31:11.766
Martin probably...

1096
01:31:11.801 --> 01:31:14.033
genuine...

1097
01:31:14.068 --> 01:31:17.588
but to be certain...

1098
01:31:17.623 --> 01:31:21.074
have deliberately...

1099
01:31:21.109 --> 01:31:25.102
revealed... my identity...

1100
01:31:25.313 --> 01:31:27.381
to enemy.

1101
01:31:27.416 --> 01:31:29.415
Stand by...

1102
01:31:29.450 --> 01:31:31.986
for confirmation...

1103
01:31:32.021 --> 01:31:35.221
in one hour.

1104
01:31:35.256 --> 01:31:39.060
<i>But if no message...</i>

1105
01:31:39.095 --> 01:31:42.664
<i>at that time...</i>

1106
01:31:42.699 --> 01:31:46.234
have been arrested...

1107
01:31:46.269 --> 01:31:49.249
therefore...

1108
01:31:49.284 --> 01:31:52.229
Martin false.

1109
01:32:34.582 --> 01:32:38.575
Come on.

1110
01:32:40.955 --> 01:32:43.791
- He had it all pat?
- Yes, about Cardiff and everything.


1111
01:32:43.826 --> 01:32:46.795
- Here's the address that he gave me.
- What's he like?


1112
01:32:46.830 --> 01:32:49.615
Tall, dark, Irish-sounding,
good-looking, about 30.


1113
01:32:49.650 --> 01:32:52.400
I'd like to get that description
to General Colbourne.


1114
01:32:52.435 --> 01:32:54.469
- May I use the phone?
- It's in there.


1115
01:32:54.504 --> 01:32:56.502
What chance that he believed you?

1116
01:32:56.537 --> 01:32:59.107
I don't know. I wasn't very good.
I wasn't ready for it.


1117
01:32:59.142 --> 01:33:01.944
- But he believed Lucy.
- You really think so?


1118
01:33:01.979 --> 01:33:04.711
Yes. He believed her, all right.
I saw his face.


1119
01:33:04.746 --> 01:33:08.739
- To Lucy it was true.
- For heaven's sake, don't start blubbering.


1120
01:33:09.317 --> 01:33:11.619
- How long did he stay?
- About 10 minutes.


1121
01:33:11.654 --> 01:33:13.986
I told him it was Lucy
that he wanted.


1122
01:33:14.021 --> 01:33:16.974
And you didn't get anything out of him
that would even give us a lead?


1123
01:33:17.009 --> 01:33:19.927
Now, steady, Monty. She got his name
and address. That wasn't too bad.


1124
01:33:19.962 --> 01:33:22.462
I didn't even have to get that.
He gave it to me.


1125
01:33:22.497 --> 01:33:25.233
General Colbourne wants us
to go round to this address and check.


1126
01:33:25.268 --> 01:33:27.535
- He's sending more men.
- Is there such an address?


1127
01:33:27.570 --> 01:33:28.735
Oh, yes.

1128
01:33:28.770 --> 01:33:32.440
It's a waste of time,
but I don't see what else we can do.


1129
01:33:32.475 --> 01:33:36.376
Don't worry.
It's all right.


1130
01:33:36.411 --> 01:33:39.180
- Leave one of your men to cover the apartment.
- Right then.


1131
01:33:39.215 --> 01:33:43.173
You lead.

1132
01:34:35.269 --> 01:34:37.870
- Good night, George.
- Cheerio, old boy.


1133
01:34:37.905 --> 01:34:41.898
Oh, I beg your pardon, sir.
I beg your pardon.


1134
01:34:50.318 --> 01:34:53.754
Why should he bother
to give Pam a phony address?


1135
01:34:53.789 --> 01:34:56.389
Why? Why?

1136
01:34:56.424 --> 01:35:00.417
Unless... George, I'm off my head.
Stop the car.


1137
01:35:00.495 --> 01:35:02.930
No, get after French and stop him.

1138
01:35:02.965 --> 01:35:05.566
- Well, make up your mind.
- Hurry, man! Hurry!


1139
01:35:12.273 --> 01:35:15.510
Blow your horn, you idiot. 
Blow your horn.

1140
01:35:21.616 --> 01:35:25.609
Let's stop rushing around like buffalo
and use our brain, if we have any.


1141
01:35:25.786 --> 01:35:28.721
Aren't I working for you anymore?
What is all this?


1142
01:35:28.756 --> 01:35:31.357
- What's the matter, sir?
- French, we're making fools of ourselves.


1143
01:35:31.392 --> 01:35:34.295
I'm inclined to agree with you, but Colbourne
feels we shouldn't take any chances.


1144
01:35:34.330 --> 01:35:36.715
- He thinks he might be there.
- That's just the point.


1145
01:35:36.750 --> 01:35:39.065
- He is there. I'm certain of it.
- Shouldn't we get on?


1146
01:35:39.100 --> 01:35:41.786
French, I want you to take your men
to the house and cover it.


1147
01:35:41.821 --> 01:35:44.431
Don't be spotted and don't do
anything else until I tell you.


1148
01:35:44.466 --> 01:35:47.041
- And if our man comes out, sir?
- Don't worry about that.


1149
01:35:47.076 --> 01:35:49.008
I'm quite sure he won't.

1150
01:35:49.043 --> 01:35:51.911
Off you go, and, mind you,
no action without further orders.


1151
01:35:51.946 --> 01:35:54.582
- You don't want us to scoop him up?
- That's exactly what I mean.


1152
01:35:54.617 --> 01:35:56.782
I'm sorry, sir,
but my orders from General...


1153
01:35:56.817 --> 01:35:59.252
I don't give a damn what your orders are.
You do as I say.


1154
01:35:59.287 --> 01:36:02.490
- I'll talk to Gen. Colbourne.
- Thank you very much, Commander.


1155
01:36:05.626 --> 01:36:07.793
- French, you have my orders. Carry them out.
- Yes, sir.


1156
01:36:07.828 --> 01:36:11.821
Just a minute, sir. Before those orders go
through, will you listen for one moment?


1157
01:36:12.567 --> 01:36:15.101
Montagu, you're taking
too much upon yourself.


1158
01:36:15.136 --> 01:36:18.205
The man almost certainly isn't there,
but if he is, he won't be there for long.


1159
01:36:18.240 --> 01:36:20.792
- Every moment we waste...
- Sir, he is there.


1160
01:36:20.827 --> 01:36:23.309
Then why are you trying
to countermand my orders?


1161
01:36:23.344 --> 01:36:26.875
General Colbourne,
if you send your men to the house...


1162
01:36:26.910 --> 01:36:30.407
you will arrest one spy,
and we may lose 30,000 men.


1163
01:36:30.484 --> 01:36:33.054
I ask you to send French
to cover the house and do no more...


1164
01:36:33.089 --> 01:36:35.688
until I've had a chance to explain.

1165
01:36:35.723 --> 01:36:39.716
- You're uncommonly sure of yourself.
- I'm sure of nothing, sir.


1166
01:36:39.794 --> 01:36:42.863
But I've used what few brains I have...

1167
01:36:42.898 --> 01:36:45.933
and now I must stand
by what they tell me.


1168
01:36:45.968 --> 01:36:48.367
Your decision, sir.

1169
01:36:48.402 --> 01:36:50.972
French, cover the house
and wait for further orders <i>from me.</i>


1170
01:36:51.007 --> 01:36:54.240
Yes, sir.

1171
01:36:54.275 --> 01:36:58.268
- Well, now, Commander?
- I'd prefer not to talk about it in the street, sir.


1172
01:37:43.257 --> 01:37:46.794
What I'm asking you to assume, sir, is...

1173
01:37:46.829 --> 01:37:48.761
that that address is genuine.

1174
01:37:48.796 --> 01:37:51.365
- If so, what happens?
- We pick him up.


1175
01:37:51.400 --> 01:37:53.418
Suppose he doesn't mind that?

1176
01:37:53.453 --> 01:37:55.401
People usually mind being shot.

1177
01:37:55.436 --> 01:37:59.305
Suppose he's prepared to risk his life
to be sure about Willie Martin.


1178
01:37:59.340 --> 01:38:03.177
If we turn up at that address,
it can only mean that we've been tipped off...


1179
01:38:03.212 --> 01:38:06.814
and that the whole
Martin story is a plant.


1180
01:38:06.849 --> 01:38:08.883
This man will have committed suicide...

1181
01:38:08.918 --> 01:38:11.336
but Jerry will know the answer...

1182
01:38:11.371 --> 01:38:13.719
and our operation will be blown.

1183
01:38:13.754 --> 01:38:17.623
I'm sorry, sir.
We mustn't touch him. We daren't.


1184
01:38:17.658 --> 01:38:20.227
You mean, till after we think
he's got a message through.


1185
01:38:20.262 --> 01:38:22.928
No, sir.
Right up till the time of the landings.


1186
01:38:22.963 --> 01:38:26.956
Because the fact that there have been no further
messages from him might give the game away.


1187
01:38:27.034 --> 01:38:29.770
You realize he'll probably be
out of the country in a couple of days.


1188
01:38:29.805 --> 01:38:32.307
Yes, and we must let him go.

1189
01:38:32.342 --> 01:38:34.809
After all, he's done us no harm.

1190
01:38:34.844 --> 01:38:37.176
Masterly inactivity.

1191
01:38:37.211 --> 01:38:41.204
They also serve
who only stand and wait.


1192
01:39:52.119 --> 01:39:55.222
Polar... bear.

1193
01:39:55.257 --> 01:39:58.409
Polar bear.

1194
01:39:58.444 --> 01:40:01.527
Martin genuine.

1195
